flowRoot.flowPara: This is a MC33926 H-Bridge used for your third motor.
Connect these to the red and black leads on motor 3
Connect these to the MOTOR POWER rail on the RIB
The RED/BLACK wires connect to 3.3v and GND and configure the module
These level shifters shift the 5v encoder signals to 3.3v for the ESP. Check your wiring twice on this section because omitting the 5v or 3.3v connection can leave you with a damaged ESP.
ALWAYS ALWAYS Connect this pin on BOTH shifters

This is an array of photodiodes and IR LEDs, When enable is high the LEDs light up and reflect off of the surface below and into the photodiodes, The output is an analog signal from 0v to 3.3v depending on how reflectave the surface is.
This pin is shared with
the H-Bridge, one enable two devices

These devices are ESCs, They're a h-bridge and some additional electronics that allow them to take a Servo Pulse on one wire instead of PWM/Direction on two. They Connect to the ESP like a servo would and draw power from the MOTOR POWER rail. Connect the RED ends to your motors RED/BLACK wires. Swap the colors to change direction.
This bank is connected to MOTOR POWER which is the battery voltage after the switch and fuse.
This jumper selects between 3.3v(red) and 5v(black). Pay attention to this jumper and make sure its set to 3.3v
This is where you connect your ESCs
Note the name of these nets, they end in 5 because they're shifted
This is where you connect your H-Bridge to MOTOR POWER
These two pins are always 5v. Connect 5v here.
The outer row on both sides is GND
Note the name of these nets, they end in 5 because they're at a higher logic level
This schematic is a simplified wiring diagram. Instead of direct connections we use net labeles, little tags on wires, to indicate where they connect to.
Additionally, We use special symbols to denote ground and power connections.
Colors are used to indicate the type of signal. Purple signals are not voltage rails. They're outputs from encoders or inputs to other modles.
The colors BLACK RED BLUE and YELLOW are used to indicate VOLTAGE RAILS.

Sometimes in the drawings a wire that is 12v is drawn as RED, This is because the wire on the physical part you are dealign with is red. This is true for the battery conection on the RIB and the connectors on the ESCs
